<div class="description">
    <h3>Description</h3>

    <div class="body">
        <p>In <a href="http://www.framework.zend.com/manual/en/zend.openid.consumer.html#zend.openid.consumer.auth">http://framework.zend.com/manual/en/â€¦</a> You can find the following "authenticate"-method:</p>

<p>public function authenticate() {
        $id = $this-&gt;_id;
        if (!empty($id)) {
            $consumer = new Zend_OpenId_Consumer();
            if (!$consumer-&gt;login($id)) {
                $ret = false;
                $msg = "Authentication failed.";
            }
        } else {
            $consumer = new Zend_OpenId_Consumer();
            if ($consumer-&gt;verify($_GET, $id)) {
                $ret = true;
                $msg = "Authentication successful";
            } else {
                $ret = false;
                $msg = "Authentication failed";
            }
        }
        return new Zend_Auth_Result($ret, $id, array($msg));
    }</p>

<p>This if-else construct doesn't make sense, because in the else-part ( which means: empty($id) ) the $consumer-&gt;verify() method uses $id, BUT it's empty!!</p>

